---
/**
 * Norway Student Visa - Long-form CRO-optimized page
 * Static page (overrides dynamic route for this specific country)
 */

import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: "overview", text: "Overview", level: 2 },
  { id: "quick-decision", text: "Quick Decision Guide", level: 2 },
  { id: "requirements", text: "Visa Requirements", level: 2 },
  { id: "insurance-requirements", text: "Insurance Requirements", level: 2 },
  { id: "recommended-providers", text: "Recommended Providers", level: 2 },
  { id: "costs", text: "Costs Breakdown", level: 2 },
  { id: "application", text: "Application Process", level: 2 },
  { id: "scenarios", text: "Real-World Scenarios", level: 2 },
  { id: "mistakes", text: "Common Mistakes", level: 2 },
  { id: "healthcare", text: "Healthcare in Norway", level: 2 },
  { id: "faq", text: "FAQ", level: 2 },
  { id: "verdict", text: "Final Verdict", level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: "Norway Health Insurance Guide", href: "/countries/norway/insurance" },
  { title: "Insurance for Students Abroad", href: "/insurance-for/students" },
  { title: "Best Expat Health Insurance", href: "/best/expat-health-insurance" },
];

const requirementsColumns = [
  { key: "requirement", header: "Requirement" },
  { key: "details", header: "Details" },
  { key: "evidence", header: "Evidence Needed" },
];

const requirementsRows = [
  { requirement: "University Admission", details: "Approved Norwegian institution", evidence: "Letter of admission" },
  { requirement: "Full Financing", details: "NOK 137,907/year (~€12,000)", evidence: "Bank account with FULL amount" },
  { requirement: "Housing", details: "Arrangement in Norway", evidence: "Rental contract or housing confirmation" },
  { requirement: "Health Insurance", details: "Until D-number registration", evidence: "Insurance certificate" },
  { requirement: "Valid Passport", details: "Valid for study duration", evidence: "Passport" },
];

const insuranceColumns = [
  { key: "feature", header: "Feature" },
  { key: "norwegian", header: "Norwegian Public (Helfo)" },
  { key: "private", header: "Private (before D-number)" },
];

const insuranceRows = [
  { feature: "Cost", norwegian: "Small copays only", private: "€50-100/month" },
  { feature: "GP Visit", norwegian: "NOK 160-200 (~€14-18)", private: "Varies by plan" },
  { feature: "Hospital", norwegian: "NOK 200/day (~€18)", private: "Varies by plan" },
  { feature: "Annual Cap", norwegian: "NOK 3,165 (~€275)", private: "Depends on plan" },
  { feature: "Required?", norwegian: "After D-number registration", private: "Until D-number" },
  { feature: "Coverage", norwegian: "Comprehensive, excellent", private: "Varies" },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: "provider", header: "Provider" },
  { key: "type", header: "Type" },
  { key: "price", header: "Cost" },
  { key: "strengths", header: "Best For" },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: "Norwegian Public (Helfo)", type: "Public", price: "Small copays", strengths: "After D-number—comprehensive, affordable" },
  { provider: "Cigna Global", type: "International", price: "$100-200/month", strengths: "Before D-number, global coverage" },
  { provider: "Allianz Care", type: "International", price: "$100-180/month", strengths: "Comprehensive private coverage" },
  { provider: "SafetyWing", type: "International", price: "$45-85/month", strengths: "Budget option before D-number" },
  { provider: "BUPA Global", type: "International", price: "$120-200/month", strengths: "Premium coverage" },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: "item", header: "Cost Item" },
  { key: "amount", header: "Amount" },
  { key: "notes", header: "Notes" },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: "Application Fee", amount: "NOK 6,300 (~€550)", notes: "Residence permit" },
  { item: "Tuition", amount: "FREE", notes: "Even for non-EU students!" },
  { item: "Semester Fee", amount: "NOK 300-600", notes: "~€25-50 per semester" },
  { item: "Healthcare Copays", amount: "Max NOK 3,165/year", notes: "~€275 annual cap" },
  { item: "Living Costs Required", amount: "NOK 137,907/year", notes: "~€12,000 (must prove FULL amount)" },
];

const timelineColumns = [
  { key: "step", header: "Step" },
  { key: "duration", header: "Timeline" },
  { key: "location", header: "Where" },
];

const timelineRows = [
  { step: "Receive university admission", duration: "3-6 months before", location: "Norwegian university" },
  { step: "Prepare financial documentation", duration: "Ensure FULL amount available", location: "Your bank" },
  { step: "Apply online for residence permit", duration: "1-3 months processing", location: "UDI website" },
  { step: "Submit biometrics", duration: "After application", location: "Embassy/police station" },
  { step: "Receive residence permit", duration: "-", location: "Embassy" },
  { step: "Arrive in Norway", duration: "-", location: "Airport" },
  { step: "Register with Tax Administration", duration: "After arrival", location: "Skatteetaten" },
  { step: "Receive D-number", duration: "2-4 weeks", location: "By mail" },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Norway Student Visa 2026: FREE Tuition, Healthcare & Application Guide"
  description="Complete guide to Norway's Student Residence Permit. FREE tuition for all students (including non-EU), affordable healthcare with small copays, and spectacular nature."
  headline="Norway Student Visa: Insurance & Requirements Guide"
  subheadline="Everything you need to know about studying in Norway—FREE tuition even for non-EU students, affordable healthcare with small copays after D-number registration, and the world's most stunning natural landscapes."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Student Insurance"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  heroImage="/images/visas/student-visa-hero-bg.png"
>

  <!-- Trust Signals -->
  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 mb-8 text-sm text-neutral-600">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Updated February 2026
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Official UDI Requirements
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      FREE Tuition for Everyone
    </span>
  </div>

  <!-- Section: Overview -->
  <section id="overview" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Norway is unique in the world: <strong>tuition is FREE at public universities for ALL students—including non-EU/EEA students</strong>. This makes Norway incredibly attractive, but there's a significant catch: you must prove you have NOK 137,907 (~€12,000) available for living expenses, and Norway has the highest living costs in Europe.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare in Norway uses small copays with an annual cap. Once you have a D-number (Norwegian ID), you access the public healthcare system. GP visits cost NOK 160-200 (~€14-18), hospital stays NOK 200/day (~€18), but everything is capped at NOK 3,165/year (~€275). After that, care is free.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Quick Facts: Norway Student Visa</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-1 text-primary-800">
        <li>• <strong>Permit Type:</strong> Student Residence Permit</li>
        <li>• <strong>Duration:</strong> 1 year, renewable</li>
        <li>• <strong>Tuition:</strong> FREE (everyone!)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Health Insurance:</strong> Small copays after D-number (max NOK 3,165/year)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Work Rights:</strong> 20 hrs/week term, full-time holidays</li>
        <li>• <strong>Financial Proof:</strong> NOK 137,907 (FULL amount required)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Processing:</strong> 1-3 months</li>
        <li>• <strong>Post-Study:</strong> 1-year job seeker permit</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Quick Decision Guide -->
  <section id="quick-decision" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Quick Decision Guide</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">✓ Norway Is a Great Fit If You:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• Have NOK 137,907 saved (seriously, this is strict)</li>
          <li>• Want free tuition regardless of nationality</li>
          <li>• Love nature, fjords, and outdoor activities</li>
          <li>• Can handle high living costs</li>
          <li>• Want to experience northern lights/midnight sun</li>
          <li>• Are okay with small healthcare copays (capped)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">⚠ Consider Alternatives If You:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Can't prove FULL financial amount upfront</li>
          <li>• Want lower living costs</li>
          <li>• Struggle with cold, dark winters</li>
          <li>• Prefer warmer climate</li>
          <li>• Want to rely entirely on work income</li>
          <li>• Prefer urban/metropolitan lifestyle (Norway is nature-focused)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Requirements -->
  <section id="requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Requirements</h2>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The critical requirement is financial proof. You must have the FULL amount (NOK 137,907) available—not income over time, but the actual amount accessible in your bank account or blocked account.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={requirementsColumns} rows={requirementsRows} />

    <div class="mt-6 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-red-800">
        <strong>⚠️ Financial Proof is STRICT:</strong> Norway requires the FULL NOK 137,907 (~€12,000) available upfront. Not income projections, not promised scholarships—actual money in your bank account. This is strictly verified. Plan accordingly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Insurance Requirements -->
  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>✓ Affordable Healthcare with D-Number:</strong> Once registered, Norwegian healthcare has small copays capped at NOK 3,165/year (~€275). After hitting the cap, care is free. GP: ~NOK 160-200. Hospital: ~NOK 200/day. Very affordable for excellent care.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Before receiving your D-number (takes 2-4 weeks after arrival), you need private insurance. EU students can use EHIC. The D-number is your key to the Norwegian system—register at Skatteetaten promptly.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={insuranceColumns} rows={insuranceRows} />

    <div class="mt-6 bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>Frikort:</strong> Once you've paid NOK 3,165 in copays during a calendar year, you receive a frikort (exemption card). After that, healthcare is free for the rest of the year. Track your payments!
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Recommended Providers -->
  <section id="recommended-providers" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Norwegian public healthcare is your primary coverage once registered. Private insurance is only needed for the initial weeks before D-number and for services not covered (dental, travel abroad).
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <CTABox
      title="Need Coverage Before D-Number?"
      description="Have comprehensive insurance for your first weeks in Norway until you're registered in the system."
      buttonText="Compare Insurance Plans"
      buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    />
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Costs -->
  <section id="costs" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Costs Breakdown</h2>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Norway's paradox: tuition is FREE, but living costs are the highest in Europe. The NOK 137,907 requirement reflects reality—you genuinely need this much to live in Norway.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

    <div class="mt-6 grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Monthly Budget (Oslo)</h4>
        <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-neutral-700">
          <li>Rent: NOK 6,000-10,000 (~€520-870)</li>
          <li>Food: NOK 3,500-5,000 (~€300-435)</li>
          <li>Transport: NOK 700-900</li>
          <li>Healthcare: NOK 0-265 (toward cap)</li>
          <li>Phone/Misc: NOK 500-1,000</li>
          <li><strong>Total: NOK 11,000-17,500/month</strong></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Monthly Budget (Bergen/Trondheim)</h4>
        <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-neutral-700">
          <li>Rent: NOK 5,000-8,000 (~€435-695)</li>
          <li>Food: NOK 3,000-4,500 (~€260-390)</li>
          <li>Transport: NOK 500-700</li>
          <li>Healthcare: NOK 0-265 (toward cap)</li>
          <li>Phone/Misc: NOK 500-800</li>
          <li><strong>Total: NOK 9,500-14,500/month</strong></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>Student Housing (Studentsamskipnad):</strong> University student housing is MUCH cheaper—NOK 3,000-5,000/month. Apply through your university's student welfare organization (Sammen, SiO, etc.) as early as possible.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Apply online through UDI (Norwegian immigration). Processing takes 1-3 months. Ensure you have housing arranged and FULL financial proof before applying.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <div class="mt-6 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-red-800">
        <strong>Housing Required:</strong> You must have housing arranged before applying. This can be a rental contract, student housing confirmation, or host family arrangement. UDI will verify this.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Real-World Scenarios -->
  <section id="scenarios" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Scenario 1: GP Visit</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2">You have flu symptoms and visit your assigned fastlege (GP).</p>
        <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> With D-number, pay NOK 160-200 (~€14-18). This counts toward your annual cap. Prescription medications have separate copays (also capped). Very affordable for excellent care.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Scenario 2: Specialist Visit</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2">Your GP refers you to a specialist.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Specialist visit: NOK 350-400. With referral, covered under public system. Counts toward your NOK 3,165 annual cap. If you've hit the cap, it's free.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Scenario 3: Emergency Room</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2">You injure yourself hiking and need emergency treatment.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> ER (legevakt) has copay of NOK 200-400. All treatment, X-rays, care included. If admitted, hospital stay: NOK 200/day. Everything counts toward annual cap.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Scenario 4: Hit the Annual Cap</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2">You've had several medical needs and paid NOK 3,165 in copays.</p>
        <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> You receive a frikort (exemption card). All remaining healthcare for the calendar year is FREE. The system automatically tracks your payments.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Scenario 5: Dental Work</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2">You need a dental checkup and cleaning.</p>
        <p class="text-red-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Dental is NOT covered by public healthcare (except emergencies). Expect NOK 800-2,000 (~€70-175) for checkup and cleaning. Budget separately or get dental insurance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Scenario 6: Before D-Number</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2">You get sick before receiving your D-number.</p>
        <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Use your private insurance or EHIC (EU students). You can access care but may pay full price and claim reimbursement. This is why you need insurance initially.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="flex gap-4 p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg">
        <div class="text-red-600 font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Not Having FULL Financial Amount</h4>
          <p class="text-red-700">This is the #1 rejection reason. You need NOK 137,907 AVAILABLE—not expected income, not future scholarship, actual money in your bank. No exceptions. Plan ahead.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4 p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg">
        <div class="text-red-600 font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Underestimating Living Costs</h4>
          <p class="text-red-700">NOK 137,907/year is the minimum. Many students need more. Norway is genuinely the most expensive country in Europe. Food, transport, entertainment—everything costs more.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4 p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg">
        <div class="text-red-600 font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">No Housing Before Applying</h4>
          <p class="text-red-700">You must have housing arranged before applying for your permit. UDI verifies this. Apply for student housing early—it's much cheaper and in high demand.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4 p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg">
        <div class="text-red-600 font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">No Insurance Before D-Number</h4>
          <p class="text-red-700">It takes 2-4 weeks to get your D-number after arrival. Until then, you need private insurance or EHIC. Don't arrive uninsured.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4 p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg">
        <div class="text-red-600 font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900">Thinking High Costs = Easy Work</h4>
          <p class="text-red-700">Yes, Norwegian wages are high. But jobs aren't unlimited, Norwegian language helps significantly, and you can only work 20 hrs/week during term. Don't plan to fund your studies entirely through work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Norway -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Norway</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Norwegian healthcare is excellent—world-class quality with small, capped copays. Once you have a D-number, you're assigned a fastlege (regular GP) and access the public system. The annual copay cap means costs are predictable.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Copay Structure (2024)</h4>
        <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-neutral-700">
          <li>GP visit: NOK 160-200 (~€14-18)</li>
          <li>Specialist (with referral): NOK 350-400</li>
          <li>Emergency (legevakt): NOK 200-400</li>
          <li>Hospital stay: NOK 200/day</li>
          <li>Prescriptions: Varies (also capped)</li>
          <li><strong>Annual cap: NOK 3,165 (~€275)</strong></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">What's NOT Covered</h4>
        <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-neutral-700">
          <li>✗ Dental care (except emergencies)</li>
          <li>✗ Glasses and contacts</li>
          <li>✗ Physiotherapy (limited coverage)</li>
          <li>✗ Cosmetic procedures</li>
          <li>✗ Some alternative medicine</li>
          <li>✗ Private healthcare</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>Helsenorge.no:</strong> Norway has an excellent digital health portal where you can see your health records, book appointments, renew prescriptions, and communicate with your GP. Very convenient once you're registered.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is tuition really free in Norway?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes! Norwegian public universities charge no tuition—even for international students. You only pay a small semester fee (NOK 300-600). This is unique in the world. The catch: you must prove NOK 137,907/year for living costs, and Norway is VERY expensive.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">How does Norwegian healthcare work for students?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After registering and getting a D-number (takes a few weeks), you access public healthcare with small copays: GP ~NOK 160-200, hospital ~NOK 200/day. Annual cap is NOK 3,165. Coverage is excellent. Until D-number: use private insurance or EHIC.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">How expensive is Norway really?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The most expensive country in Europe. Budget NOK 12,000-15,000/month minimum (€1,000-1,300). Rent in Oslo: NOK 6,000-10,000/month for a room. Food is expensive. Alcohol is very expensive. Student housing helps significantly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I work while studying in Norway?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. During semester: 20 hours/week. During semester breaks: full-time. No separate work permit needed. Wages are high (NOK 150-200/hour common for student jobs) but so are costs. Many students work to supplement savings.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">What is the D-number?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Temporary Norwegian identification number for people not permanently resident. You need it for healthcare, banking, employment. Register at the Tax Office after arrival. Processing: 2-4 weeks. Once you've been in Norway longer, you get a full national ID number.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I stay after graduation?</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Graduates can apply for a 1-year job seeker permit. If you find skilled employment, you can get a work permit. Norway also has a skilled worker immigration program. The job market is good for tech, engineering, and oil/energy sectors.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
